body:
This closes https://github.com/cython/cython/issues/2741

I have a feeling that I'm not using Node properties correctly, e.g. `is_literal`
Where can I find contribution docs for it?

Thanks

comment_data.body: This transforms something like `frozenset([])` into `frozenset()`. It just avoids building an empty list/tuple/whatever.
comment_data.diff_hunk:
@@ -1990,6 +1990,7 @@ def _handle_simple_function_frozenset(self, node, pos_args):
         """
         if len(pos_args) != 1:
             return node
+        # TODO Doubt: What's the case for it
         if pos_args[0].is_sequence_constructor and not pos_args[0].args:
             del pos_args[0]

comment_data.body:
I suspect this is code that you're just moving from elsewhere, but doctest [does support testing that an exception is raised](https://docs.python.org/3/library/doctest.html#what-about-exceptions). So it's be something like:

```
>>> test_set_contains([1, 2])  # doctest: +IGNORE_EXCEPTION_DETAIL
Traceback (most recent call last):
    ...
TypeError: ...
```

(use `+IGNORE_EXCEPTION_DETAIL` or `+ELLIPSIS` as needed depending on if you care about the exact error message)

You still need to use `__Pyx_PyFrozenSet_New()` here, and add the utility code from `UtilityCode.load_cached('pyfrozenset_new', 'Builtins.c')`.

Also, why is this not calling the set creation method above?

comment_data.body: Note that the `dedup_key` contains a values tuple which may have duplicate entries. For a set key, pass it through `frozenset()` to deduplicate the items. And then make sure that you test this with objects that compare equal but aren't the same, e.g. byte and unicode strings or int and float values.

comment_data.body: Sure. I'll move these tests to set.pyx

Currently, we have lots of checks like `if len(args) > 1` in `set/frozenset` construction

If we don't expect change of `set()` definition (only 0 or 1 argument), can we throw an exception if there're more than one arguments?
